The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Andrew Yule posts profit
                                                                                                               Andrew Yule posts profit
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, June 30: Public sector Andrew Yule has posted a net profit for the second year in a row, after being declared sick seven years ago.        
	Andrew Yule chairman Kallol Datta said the company had posted a net profit of Rs 29 crore, buoyed by higher tea prices and a good performance of the electrical and engineering divisions. Last fiscal, Yule had posted a net profit of Rs 8 crore. Sales in 2008-09 stood at Rs 189 crore against Rs 182 crore a year ago.        
	EIH profit falls        
	EIHs consolidated profit fell 23 per cent in 2008-09 to Rs 169.95 crore as the global financial crisis and terrorist attacks on its hotels in Mumbai hit business. The company had a profit of Rs 221.50 crore in 2007-08.        
	Bridge and Roof        
	Bridge and Roof Companys (India) sales turnover rose 31 per cent to Rs 935.07 crore in 2008-09 from Rs 714.79 crore in 2007-08.         
	The company hopes to touch the Rs 2,000-crore mark in sales turnover over the next three years, chairman Mukesh Jha said today.        
	Net profit would be about 30 per cent less than its profit before tax.        
	The companys current order book stands at Rs 1,850 crore, which it expects to take to Rs 2,000 crore by March 2010.        
	We are exploring further opportunities to jointly work with private companies engaged in the construction business, both as JV partners and on subcontract basis. Jha added.        
	Electrosteel Castings         
	Ductile iron pipe maker Electrosteels profit rose 170 per cent to Rs 140.39 crore from Rs 52.02 crore in 2007-08.         
	Graphite India        
	Graphite Indias income grew 12 per cent to Rs 1,557.86 crore from Rs 1,388.36 crore in the preceding year, while net profit was up 65 per cent to Rs 235.52 crore from Rs 142.34 crore.                                                                                                                                              
